<subSubSection id="C36A6CC71936FF83E3A2F8A97DBF0AB2" pageId="2" pageNumber="484" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BCF3F4C1936FF83E3A2F8A97DBF0AB2" blockId="2.[151,1437,1509,2003]" pageId="2" pageNumber="484">
<emphasis id="B904E35E1936FF83E3A2F8A97C1F0A5E" bold="true" box="[199,334,1870,1895]" pageId="2" pageNumber="484">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is in honor of Anabelle Aurelia Tapia for her help collecting Ecuadorian spiders.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36A6CC71936FF82E3A2F87179430C25" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="485" pageId="2" pageNumber="484" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCF3F4C1936FF82E3A2F87179430C25" blockId="2.[151,1437,1509,2003]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,1149]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="485" pageId="2" pageNumber="484">
<emphasis id="B904E35E1936FF83E3A2F8717C100A96" bold="true" box="[199,321,1942,1967]" pageId="2" pageNumber="484">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males are distinguished from most species by their swollen metatarsus I without cusp (
<figureCitation id="134B23C91936FF83E67BF87178320A96" box="[1310,1379,1942,1967]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1955]" captionTargetBox="[203,1380,209,1897]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[201,1387,195,1909]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Anapis anabelleae n. sp. 1, Male palp prolateral view. 2, Male palp retrolateral view. 2a, Male palp conductor and embolus, retrolateral view. 3, Male left metatarsus and tarsus I, prolateral view. 4, Male, left metatarsus and tarsus II, prolateral view. 5, Female epigastric region, ventral view. 6, Female internal genitalia, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458816/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="484">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) and the angular conductor of the palp (
<figureCitation id="134B23C91936FF83E176F85D7FF00AEA" box="[531,673,1978,2003]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1955]" captionTargetBox="[203,1380,209,1897]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[201,1387,195,1909]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Anapis anabelleae n. sp. 1, Male palp prolateral view. 2, Male palp retrolateral view. 2a, Male palp conductor and embolus, retrolateral view. 3, Male left metatarsus and tarsus I, prolateral view. 4, Male, left metatarsus and tarsus II, prolateral view. 5, Female epigastric region, ventral view. 6, Female internal genitalia, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458816/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="484">Figs 1, 2, 2a</figureCitation>
); from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7044CF1936FF83E197F85C7EC30AEA" authorityName="PlatNick &amp; SHadab" authorityYear="1978" box="[754,914,1979,2003]" class="Arachnida" family="Anapidae" genus="Anapis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monteverde">
<emphasis id="B904E35E1936FF83E197F85C7EC30AEA" box="[754,914,1979,2003]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="484">A. monteverde</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are distinguished by the presence of three to four cusps on tarsus II (
<figureCitation id="134B23C91937FF82E2ABFF707F470D89" box="[462,534,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1955]" captionTargetBox="[203,1380,209,1897]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[201,1387,195,1909]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Anapis anabelleae n. sp. 1, Male palp prolateral view. 2, Male palp retrolateral view. 2a, Male palp conductor and embolus, retrolateral view. 3, Male left metatarsus and tarsus I, prolateral view. 4, Male, left metatarsus and tarsus II, prolateral view. 5, Female epigastric region, ventral view. 6, Female internal genitalia, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458816/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="485">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), one in the latter species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE142BD1937FF82E031FF7079830D89" box="[852,1234,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="485" refId="ref12803" refString="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Shadab, M. U. (1978) A review of the spider genus Anapis (Araneae, Anapidae), with a dual cladistic analysis. American Museum Novitates, 2663, 1 - 23." type="journal article">Platnick &amp; Shadab 1978, fig. 26</bibRefCitation>
). Females can be distinguished from most species by straight copulatory ducts (
<figureCitation id="134B23C91937FF82E015FF5B7EE80DEC" box="[880,953,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1955]" captionTargetBox="[203,1380,209,1897]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[201,1387,195,1909]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Anapis anabelleae n. sp. 1, Male palp prolateral view. 2, Male palp retrolateral view. 2a, Male palp conductor and embolus, retrolateral view. 3, Male left metatarsus and tarsus I, prolateral view. 4, Male, left metatarsus and tarsus II, prolateral view. 5, Female epigastric region, ventral view. 6, Female internal genitalia, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458816/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="485">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7044CF1937FF82E770FF5B79EA0DED" authorityName="PlatNick &amp; SHadab" authorityYear="1978" box="[1045,1211,188,212]" class="Arachnida" family="Anapidae" genus="Anapis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="485" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monteverde">
<emphasis id="B904E35E1937FF82E770FF5B79EA0DED" box="[1045,1211,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="485">A. monteverde</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by their unpointed abdomen (
<figureCitation id="134B23C91937FF82E26EFF387C0E0DC1" box="[267,351,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–53" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1912,1935]" captionTargetBox="[224,1366,197,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[199,1385,193,1886]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 46–53. Habitus, lateral view. 46, Male Anapis anabelleae n. sp. 47, Female Anapis anabelleae n. sp. 48, Male Anapis carmencita n. sp. 49, Female Anapis carmencita n. sp. 50, Male Anapis churu n. sp. 51, Male Anapis mariebertheae n. sp. 52, Male Anapis naranja n. sp. 53, Female Anapis naranja n. sp. Scale bars: 0.5mm" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458835/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="485">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
), pointed in the latter (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE142BD1937FF82E13FFF387E200DC1" box="[602,881,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="485" refId="ref12803" refString="Platnick, N. I. &amp; Shadab, M. U. (1978) A review of the spider genus Anapis (Araneae, Anapidae), with a dual cladistic analysis. American Museum Novitates, 2663, 1 - 23." type="journal article">Platnick &amp; Shadab 1978</bibRefCitation>
); from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7044CF1937FF82E0A4FF07794C0DC1" authority="Dupérré &amp; Tapia, 2018" authorityName="Dupérré &amp; Tapia" authorityYear="2018" box="[961,1053,224,248]" class="Arachnida" family="Anapidae" genus="Anapis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="485" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shina" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B904E35E1937FF82E0A4FF07794C0DC1" box="[961,1053,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="485">A. shina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2375E251937FF82E746FF3879330DCE" box="[1059,1122,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="485" rank="species">
<emphasis id="B904E35E1937FF82E746FF38790B0DC1" bold="true" box="[1059,1114,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="485">n. sp</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
by their shorter fertilization ducts and longer copulatory ducts (
<figureCitation id="134B23C91937FF82E17AFEE37F320C24" box="[543,611,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1932,1955]" captionTargetBox="[203,1380,209,1897]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[201,1387,195,1909]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Anapis anabelleae n. sp. 1, Male palp prolateral view. 2, Male palp retrolateral view. 2a, Male palp conductor and embolus, retrolateral view. 3, Male left metatarsus and tarsus I, prolateral view. 4, Male, left metatarsus and tarsus II, prolateral view. 5, Female epigastric region, ventral view. 6, Female internal genitalia, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458816/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="485">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) inverse in the latter species (
<figureCitation id="134B23C91937FF82E0D5FEE379570C25" box="[944,1030,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 38–43" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[234,1366,211,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[219,1368,193,1889]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 38–43. Anapis shina n. sp. 38, Male palp prolateral view. 39, Male palp retrolateral view. 39a. Male palp conductor and embolus, retrolateral view. 40, Male left metatarsus and tarsus I, prolateral view. 41, Male, left metatarsus and tarsus II, prolateral view. 42, Female epigastric region, ventral view. 43, Female internal genitalia, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458830/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="485">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
